I‚Äôm a young millennial and so many people my age feel stuck in this weird in-between.  

Too late to buy affordable property and too early for the TikTok or Instagram creator wave but the irony is we are perfectly positioned for something bigger. 

We get to participate in the early innings of the largest industrial buildout since the internet with trillions in capex pouring into the physical layer of the AI economy and we‚Äôre early enough to capture it in real time: 

‚Ä¢ $NVDA & $AMD are building the compute layer 
‚Ä¢ $TSLA is pushing the robotics layer 
‚Ä¢ $PLTR is defining the intelligence layer
‚Ä¢ $AMZN, $MSFT & $GOOGL are owning the cloud layer
‚Ä¢ $META shapes the attention layer
‚Ä¢ $CRWD secures the security layer.

Going all-in on AI in 2023 is the reason I‚Äôm not stressed about being ‚Äúbehind.‚Äù Most people my age don‚Äôt realize it yet but this is our generation‚Äôs moment.

$META just secured a wave of AI data deals with major news publishers including USA Today, People, CNN & Fox News. 

Meta is clearly building a broader training pipeline by locking in commercial access to premium newsroom data.

This is the cleanest snapshot of who is actually manufacturing the AI economy and who is leasing their way into it. 

$GOOGL, $MSFT, $META & $AMZN can push 50-80% of operating cash flow into capex without stressing the balance sheet which is why they will continue to define the pace of AI compute, networking & data-center buildouts.

$ORCL, by contrast, is carrying 4x the leverage to chase the same cycle which is why the market has been repricing their stock over the past month. $CRWV sits above 7x because their economics only work if they scale quickly enough to refinance on better terms. 

I do think Oracle is placing a very large, very concentrated and very expensive bet on the long-term structure of the AI economy. The payoff can be substantial if demand remains this tight and if Oracle can genuinely deploy usable GPU capacity faster than the hyperscalers.

Goldman Sachs Reiterates Buy on $AMZN, PT $290

Analyst comments: "We recap Amazon's annual AWS re:Invent conference, where management outlined a range of new product and service announcements tied to their view of how the public cloud industry will evolve, particularly in artificial intelligence, machine learning, and custom silicon. Combined with Amazon‚Äôs recent earnings report, we view the key takeaways from re:Invent and management‚Äôs forward narrative as another positive step in improving investor sentiment around AWS‚Äôs artificial intelligence thematic positioning.

We see these two events‚Äîearnings and re:Invent‚Äîas supportive of (a) Amazon‚Äôs ability to re-accelerate revenue growth and (b) the role AWS will play as the artificial intelligence theme expands from a small set of foundational models to broader deployment (agents), development (applications), and workload migration (requiring lower costs and greater efficiencies) for enterprise customers. In many ways, AWS‚Äôs framing of the artificial intelligence opportunity reflects hallmarks of its e-commerce success: breadth of supply, ease of purchase and partnership, matching demand and supply at scale, and a singular customer-focused platform mindset.

Management‚Äôs presentations imply that AWS‚Äôs strategic priority is to position the company to capitalize on the rise‚Äîand eventual ubiquity‚Äîof artificial intelligence, similar to how prior shifts in compute, storage, and databases shaped earlier phases of cloud industry growth. We also refresh our recent fundamental work on the current cloud landscape and AWS‚Äôs forward growth opportunity. We remain confident in our view that AWS can achieve roughly a 20%+ revenue compound annual growth rate over the next three years."

Analyst: Eric Sheridan
